$* To discover alive host/s in a network.
# nmap -sn <IP>  OR  nmap -sP <IP> 
         -> Here, -sP ping scan (old option to check if host is up no port scan)
                  -sn no port scan ( modern option skip port scan , just do host discovery)
# nmap -R -sn <IP> 
         -> with -R nmap tries to check host name (reverse DNS) even if host is dead.

$* effecient way to use.
# nmap -sn <IP subnet> -oG hosts.txt
         -> To store the result in a file.
         here, -oG is for greppable output
                hosts.txt is file name containing the result of -sn command ie ip , status and hostname (if resolved).
# grep Up hosts.txt | awk '{print $2}' > live_hosts.txt
         -> To store the alive IPs into a file.
         here, with grep takes the line which has status "Up".
               then print second field ie IPs in the live_hosts.txt file
                   ( Host: 192.168.1.5 (printer.local)   Status: Up) $2 is IP

         

         
